{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645452"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:18:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:18:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18115"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18115"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0,0.48,0,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10829"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78291"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10829"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18115"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63686"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3000"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7167"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25202"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25205"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26858"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78291"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe brachial plexus is a network of nerves that supplies the upper limb. It is formed by the anterior rami of the spinal nerves C5 to T1. The plexus is divided into roots, trunks, divisions, cords, and branches.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves originates from the C5 and C6 nerve roots via the upper trunk of the brachial plexus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Axillary","Long thoracic","Musculocutaneous","Radial","Suprascapular"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuprascapular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E originates from the upper trunk of the brachial plexus, which is formed by the union of the C5 and C6 nerve roots. It innervates the supraspinatus and infraspinatus muscles of the shoulder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAxillary nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve arises from the posterior cord of the brachial plexus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMusculocutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve arises from the lateral cord of the brachial plexus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve arises from the posterior cord of the brachial plexus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELong thoracic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve arises from the roots of C5, C6, and C7\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The suprascapular nerve originates from the upper trunk of the brachial plexus, which is formed by the union of the C5 and C6 nerve roots.","The brachial plexus is a network of nerves that supplies the upper limb, originating from the spinal nerve roots C5 to T1.","Understanding the origin and pathway of nerves in the brachial plexus is crucial for diagnosing nerve injuries."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medici